43:55.600 --> 43:59.474
♪ She's gonna blow your house down ♪

43:59.475 --> 44:02.140
See, you guys are stopping,

44:02.141 --> 44:04.557
and underneath your stop,

44:04.558 --> 44:06.557
Larry is coming in

44:06.558 --> 44:09.766
on the tom-tom, on the bass
drum, starts playing it again,

44:09.767 --> 44:11.265
so it never really stops.

44:11.266 --> 44:13.057
- Yeah.
- I think that could work.

44:13.058 --> 44:15.932
A great idea has a lot in common

44:15.933 --> 44:16.973
with a great melody,

44:16.974 --> 44:20.599
and Jimmy's gift is the clear thought.

44:20.600 --> 44:22.766
But also outside of music,

44:22.767 --> 44:24.766
in the room, the clear thought.

44:24.767 --> 44:27.349
When others hear
harmony or counterpoint,

44:27.350 --> 44:28.766
he hears the clear melody.

44:28.767 --> 44:30.557
So he applies that wherever he is.

44:30.558 --> 44:33.557
Why don't you sing what you
sang me when I first got here?

44:33.558 --> 44:36.265
- Um...
- Do you remember it?

44:36.266 --> 44:37.641
Yeah, well, that was more like...

44:37.642 --> 44:39.599
- It was more like...
- It was a little different than that.

44:39.600 --> 44:41.098
There was a little more to it.

44:41.099 --> 44:44.182
It was more like a... lyrical idea.

44:44.183 --> 44:46.682
It sounded really good.

44:46.683 --> 44:48.432
Bono and I hit it off.

44:48.433 --> 44:49.848
We became friends.

44:49.849 --> 44:54.099
But that was the beginning
of, um, a tough time for me.

45:05.141 --> 45:07.807
Jerry, Yella's on One.

45:07.808 --> 45:11.349
You know, you're talkin'
about the most controversial time

45:11.350 --> 45:13.557
in the history of the music business.

